Multidimensional Two Parameter Logistic Model with Predictors

Erick A. Chacon-Montalvan

2018-05-22

In this vignette, we show how to use the spifa package to fit a multidimensional 2 parameter logistic model used in item response theory. Let \(Y_{ij}\) be the response for item \(j\) in the individual \(i\). The model can be defined by using an auxiliary variable \(Z_{ij}\) such as \[\begin{align} {Y}_{ij} & = \left\lbrace \begin{array}[2]{cc} 1 & \text{if} ~ {Z}_{ij} > 0\\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{array} \right.\\ {Z}_{ij} & = c_j + a_j^\intercal\theta_i + \epsilon_{ij}, ~~ \epsilon_{ij} \sim {N}(0, 1)\\ {\theta}_i & \sim {N}({0}, {I}_m)\\ c_j & \sim {N}(0, \sigma_c^2)\\ {a}_j & \sim {N}(0, \sigma_a^2{I}_m)\\ \end{align}\]

Required packages

rm(list = ls())
# library(spifa)

Simulation of the data

Firtst, simulate correlated factors:

m <- 2
# set.seed(4)
Corr <- matrix(c(1, -0.3, -0.3, 1), nrow = m)
sigmas <- rep(0.3^0.5, m)
D <- diag(sigmas)
Cov <- D %*% Corr %*% D
beta1 <- c(sqrt(0.5), -sqrt(0.4))
beta2 <- c(sqrt(0.2), sqrt(0.3))

# mean ~ mre(factor(id), sigma = get("Cov")),
f <- list(
  mean ~ mfe(x1, beta = get("beta1")) +
    mfe(x2, beta = get("beta2")) +
    mre(factor(id), sigma = get("Cov")),
  sd ~ I(0)
  )

n <- 300
(data_factor <- sim_model(formula = f, n = n, responses = m))

First, we define the parameters for the item response model.

q <- q1 <- q2 <- 10
init_data <- purrr::map(1:q, ~ data_factor_wide) %>%
  purrr::reduce(rbind)

n <- 300
difficulty <- matrix((1:q - 5)/10 * 2, nrow = 1)
discrimination1 <- seq(0.4, 1.5, length.out = q)
discrimination2 <- runif(q, 0, 2)

discrimination1[1] = 1
discrimination2[2] = 1
discrimination1[c(4, 8)] <- 0
discrimination2[c(1, 5, 9)] <- 0

Now we simulate the data using the datasim package.

f <- list(
  prob ~ mfa(ones, beta = get("difficulty")) +
    mfe(ability1, beta = get("discrimination1")) +
    mfe(ability2, beta = get("discrimination2")),
  size ~ I(1)
  )

data_long <- sim_model(formula = f,
                        link_inv = list(pnorm, identity),
                        generator = rbinom,
                        responses = q,
                        n = n,
                        init_data = init_data
                        )

data_long <- dplyr::rename(data_long, subject = id,
                           item = response_label, y = response)

Exploratory analysis

We can see the relationship between the latent abilities and the proportion of endorsed items.

explor <- data_long %>%
  group_by(subject) %>%
  summarize(endorse = mean(y),
            ability1 = unique(ability1),
            ability2 = unique(ability2),
            x1 = unique(x1),
            x2 = unique(x2))
ggplot(explor, aes(ability1, endorse)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

ggplot(explor, aes(ability2, endorse)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

ggplot(explor, aes(x1, endorse)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

ggplot(explor, aes(x2, endorse)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.5)

Fitting the model

iter <- 5 * 10 ^ 4
thin <- 10
disc_mat <- cbind(cbind(discrimination1), cbind(discrimination2))
L_a <- lower.tri(disc_mat, diag = TRUE) * 1

L_a[c(4, 8), 1] <- 0
L_a[c(5, 9),2] <- 0

# L_a <- matrix(1, q, 2)
# L_a[c(1, 5, 8, 16)] <- 0
theta_init <- c(data_long$ability1[1:n], data_long$ability2[1:n])
a_init <- as.numeric(t(disc_mat))
a_mean <- matrix(0, q, 2)
diag(a_mean) <- 1
# a_mean[1,] <- 1

predictors <- as.matrix(dplyr::select(data_factor_wide, x1:x2))

Rcpp::sourceCpp("../src/ifa-driver.cpp")
source("../R/check-arguments.R")
source("../R/spifa-ggplot.R")
source("../R/spifa-methods.R")
source("../R/spifa.R")


iter = 10^3
thin = 1
system.time(
samples <- spifa(
  response = data_long$y, predictors = predictors, coordinates = NULL,
  nobs = n, nitems = q, nfactors = 2, niter = iter, thin = thin,
  # standardize = FALSE,
  # constrains = list(A = L_a, V_sd = sigmas) ,
  constrains = list(A = L_a, V_sd = rep(0.3, 2)) ,
  # adaptive = list(Sigma_R = matrix(0.001, 1,1))
  A_opt = list(initial = L_a),
  R_opt = list(prior_eta = 1)
)
)

Prediction

newdata = matrix(rnorm(100), ncol = 2)

bla <- predict(samples, newdata = newdata, burnin = iter / 2, thin = 1)

as_tibble.spifa.list(bla) %>%
  dplyr::select(1:10) %>%
  gg_trace()

as_tibble.spifa.list(bla) %>%
  dplyr::select(1:10) %>%
  gg_density(ridges = TRUE)
#> Picking joint bandwidth of 0.112

as_tibble.spifa.list(bla) %>%
  summary() %>%
  mutate(
  x1 = rep(newdata[,1], m),
  x2 = rep(newdata[,2], m),
  ability = rep(1:m, each = nrow(newdata))) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(x1, `50%`, col = "x1")) +
  geom_point(aes(x2, `50%`, col = "x2")) +
  facet_wrap(~ability) +
  coord_fixed()
